{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"qiMZ/z8f6KBGLOHJkzNCRE+V350=","kind":"spec","title":"kref local-file tracking — B4: write-back — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"MpJWVKrpdG97onPGFcSxNgs65P4=","body":"# kref local-file tracking — B4: write-back — design\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-26\n**Status:** APPROVED — engine implemented; CLI surface revised (see below).\n**Scope:** Add the entry → file direction as a new `--write` mode on `kref\nreconcile`. Default `reconcile` still pulls (file → entry, unchanged). With\n`--write` it pushes the entry's body back out to its tracked file when the file\nis safely behind, and surfaces a unified diff (entry ↔ file) when the file has\ndiverged so the user can choose to pull (plain `reconcile`) or force the push.\nBuilds on B1 (tracking), B2 (reconcile/pull), B3 (drift).\n\n**Naming note (revised during implementation):** the command name `sync` is\nalready taken — it is kref's *remote-tier* push/pull family (`kref sync\npush`/`pull`, in the \"Sync Commands\" group). So write-back is exposed as\n`reconcile --write`, and the engine is named `bridge.WriteBack` (not\n`SyncEntry`) with action label `written` (not `pushed`), to keep \"sync\"\nexclusively meaning remote-tier in this codebase.\n\n## 1. Key idea — the op-log is the merge oracle; no new storage\n\nB3 stored no \"last-synced\" baseline, and B4 still adds none. The entry's body\nhistory `Store.BodyVersions(id)` already records **every body the entry has ever\nhad** (each create/ingest/reconcile/edit appends a `SetBody` op). That set is the\noracle:\n\n- Let **F** = the tracked file's current body (trailer stripped, trailing\n  newlines trimmed — same normalization as `ReconcileEntry`).\n- Let **H** = the entry head body (`snap.Body`).\n- Let **V** = the set of bodies in `BodyVersions` (same normalization; the\n  create-time body is included because `Store.Add` appends a `SetBody`).\n\nThe asymmetry that drives the whole design:\n\n- **Pull (file → entry) is non-destructive** — the entry is an append-only\n  op-log; a superseded body is always recoverable via `kref diff` / `BodyVersions`.\n- **Push (entry → file) is destructive** — it overwrites a loose file that has\n  no history of its own.\n\nSo `V` answers the only question that gates the destructive direction: *does the\nfile carry edits the entry never saw?* If `F ∈ V`, the file is exactly a past\nentry state — it has **no** unsynced edits, so a push cannot lose anything. If\n`F ∉ V`, the file was edited independently.\n\n## 2. Classification \u0026 action (per tracked entry)\n\nClassification is on **body** (V is body history; title rides along inside the\nbody as its H1 and is written as part of the body on push).\n\n| State | Condition | Meaning | `reconcile --write` action |\n|-------|-----------|---------|---------------|\n| `in-sync` | `F == H` | nothing changed | no-op |\n| `missing` | file absent at `TrackedPath` | file deleted | skip + report (no re-create, no relocate self-heal) |\n| `written` | `F ∈ V`, `F != H` | entry advanced, file untouched | **push** entry → file (safe fast-forward) |\n| `diverged` | `F ∉ V` | file has edits the entry never saw | **refuse + show unified diff**; user resolves |\n| `forced` | `F ∉ V`, `--force` | user overrode divergence | **push** entry → file (overwrites file edits), loud WARNING |\n| `error` | I/O failure | — | report, continue, nonzero exit |\n\n**The honest limitation (and why `diverged` refuses).** Without a stored\nlast-synced marker, when `F ∉ V` we cannot tell \"only the file changed\" (a plain\npull) from \"both changed\" (a true conflict) — they are byte-identical situations.\nSo `--write` does **not** auto-pick a direction there. It prints the entry ↔ file\ndiff and the two resolutions:\n\n- `kref reconcile \u003cid|path\u003e` → pull (file wins; non-destructive), or\n- `kref reconcile \u003cid|path\u003e --write --force` → push (entry wins; overwrites the\n  file's edits).\n\nThis is why `--write`'s only automatic write is the safe FF push (`written`). The\ndefault `reconcile` (no `--write`) is the pull path, unchanged; `--write` adds\npush + conflict surfacing on the same command.\n\n## 3. No secret scan on write-back\n\nPer the approved decision: `--write` does **not** secret-scan. The body is already\nstored (it passed `ingest`'s D3 guard or was authored in-store), and write-back\nonly touches local disk — it never reaches a remote, unlike `reconcile`'s pull\nwhich can carry a file secret into a tier that may be pushed. (The pull path keeps\nits fail-closed scan; `--write` does not add one.)\n\n## 4. Mechanism\n\n### 4.1 Engine — `internal/bridge/bridge.go`\n\n```go\n// WriteBackResult reports the outcome of writing one tracked entry back to its\n// file (entry → file).\ntype WriteBackResult struct {\n    ID     entity.Id `json:\"id\"`\n    Path   string    `json:\"path\"`  // repo-relative tracked path\n    Title  string    `json:\"title\"`\n    Action string    `json:\"action\"` // in-sync | written | missing | diverged | forced | error\n    Diff   string    `json:\"diff,omitempty\"`  // unified entry↔file diff, set when diverged/forced\n    Error  string    `json:\"error,omitempty\"`\n}\n\n// WriteBack pushes entry snap.ID's body out to its tracked file (entry → file).\n// It writes only when the file is a safe fast-forward (its current body is a\n// past entry version, F ∈ V) or, with force, when the file diverged. A diverged\n// file (F ∉ V) without force is reported with a unified entry↔file diff and not\n// written. A missing file is reported and skipped. dryRun computes the action\n// (and diverged diff) without writing.\nfunc WriteBack(s *store.Store, snap *entry.Snapshot, dryRun, force bool, actor, actorKind string) (WriteBackResult, error)\n```\n\nLogic:\n\n1. Read file at `snap.TrackedPath`. `os.IsNotExist` → `missing`, return.\n2. `F = TrimRight(splitMarkerBody)`. If `F == H` → `in-sync`, return.\n3. Load `V` via `s.BodyVersions(snap.ID)` (normalize each). Membership test:\n   - `F ∈ V` → `written`. If `!dryRun`: write `withMarker(H, id)` to the file\n     (re-stamps the kref-id trailer), then `RecordOrigin(id, actor, actorKind,\n     path, \"writeback\")`.\n   - `F ∉ V` → compute `Diff` = unified diff (entry head vs file body). Then:\n     - `force` → `forced`; write as above (overwrites). Caller emits a loud,\n       tier-named WARNING (mirrors reconcile's forced-secret WARNING).\n     - else → `diverged`; write nothing.\n4. `dryRun` never writes; `diverged`/`forced` still carry `Diff`.\n\nAfter a `written`/`forced` write, `F == H`, so the next write-back is `in-sync`,\nand the file's trailer is restored if it had been stripped.\n\n### 4.2 Unified diff — in `internal/bridge`\n\nThe diff is produced entirely in the engine (`WriteBack` sets `res.Diff`), so it\nlives in `bridge`, not `render`: `render` is documented **pure** (stdlib +\n`internal/entry` only) and `difflib` would break that. Add an unexported\n`unifiedDiff(entryBody, fileBody string) (string, error)` to `bridge.go` using\n`github.com/pmezard/go-difflib/difflib` (`difflib.GetUnifiedDiffString` with\n`FromFile: \"entry\"`, `ToFile: \"file\"`, `Context: 3`). The dep is already in\n`go.sum` as indirect (MIT); B4 promotes it to a direct `require`. It is exercised\nthrough `WriteBack`'s `Diff` field (no separate exported API). (`kref diff` keeps\nits full-version rendering — unchanged.)\n\n### 4.3 CLI — `--write` mode on `newReconcileCmd` in `cmd/kref/commands.go`\n\nWrite-back is a new `--write` flag on the existing `reconcile` command (no new\ncommand, no new registration). Default `reconcile` pulls (unchanged); `--write`\nflips to push (entry → file):\n\n```\nkref reconcile [\u003cid|path\u003e]            Reconcile a tracked file with its entry\n  (default)        pull  file → entry (B2/B3, unchanged)\n  --write          push  entry → file (write-back; this slice)\n  -y, --yes        skip the sweep confirmation prompt\n      --force      pull mode: override the secret guard;\n                   --write mode: overwrite a diverged file with its entry\n      --dry-run    report (and, with --write, show diffs) without writing\n```\n\n- **Targets:** shared with the pull path — one `\u003cid|path\u003e` (must be `Tracked`)\n  or, with no arg, a sweep over every tracked entry.\n- **Branch:** after resolving targets, `--write` dispatches to an extracted\n  `reconcileWrite` helper (keeps `newReconcileCmd` readable); without it the\n  existing pull loop runs verbatim.\n- **Confirm prompt (`--write` sweep, not `--dry-run`):** state the count, and\n  when `--force` is set name the destructive overwrite (\"… will OVERWRITE any\n  diverged file\"). `-y` skips it.\n- **Per-entry output:** one line per non-`in-sync` entry (`action  shortid\n  path`); for `diverged`/`forced`, print the `Diff` block beneath it; for\n  `diverged`, also print the two resolution hints. `forced` prints the WARNING to\n  stderr.\n- **Summary line:** `wrote N: a written, b in-sync, c missing, d diverged,\n  e forced, f error`.\n- **`--json`:** emit `[]WriteBackResult` (the machine interface; `Diff` included).\n- **Exit code:** nonzero if any `diverged` (unresolved) or `error` remains, so\n  `kref reconcile --write \u0026\u0026 …` gates on a clean tree (like git's conflict exit).\n  `--force` that resolves all divergence → exit 0.\n\n## 5. Slices (TDD)\n\nEach slice: RED (failing test) → GREEN (implement) → commit on `main`. Run the\nfull `-tags e2e -race -shuffle=on` suite before each commit.\n\n- **A. Engine classify + write (done, commit `73bf474`).** `bridge.WriteBack`\n  for `in-sync`, `written` (F ∈ V → file rewritten with trailer; provenance\n  \"writeback\"), `missing`, and `dryRun` (no write). Tests mirror `bridge_test.go`\n  `Ingest`+`Track` setup.\n- **B. Diverged + diff + force (done, commit `8f68251`).** `F ∉ V` → `diverged`\n  with non-empty `Diff`, file untouched; `--force` → `forced`, file overwritten;\n  diff exercised through `WriteBack.Diff`; `go.mod` direct require added.\n- **C. CLI `reconcile --write`.** Add `--write` to `newReconcileCmd`; branch to\n  `reconcileWrite` helper. Single + sweep, confirm prompt (+ `--force` wording),\n  `-y`, `--dry-run`, `--json`, exit code on unresolved divergence. Tests mirror\n  `cli_test.go` `run`/`runWithIn` patterns. No new command registration.\n\n## 6. Out of scope\n\n- Auto-pull on divergence, 3-way content merge, conflict markers in files.\n- Re-creating or relocating a missing file (skip + report only).\n- Any new persisted op or hash (the op-log remains the only baseline).\n- Changing the default (no-`--write`) `reconcile` pull path.\n\n\u003e **Note:** Slices A/B were committed under the engine names `SyncEntry`/\n\u003e `SyncResult`/action `pushed`; slice C renames them to `WriteBack`/\n\u003e `WriteBackResult`/`written` (the `sync` name collides with kref's remote-tier\n\u003e command). The rename rides in the slice-C engine commit."}]}